  <p>
    A good minimal habit tracker gets out of your way: fast capture, clear feedback, and no project-management overhead.
    Memoato keeps those principles, then goes one step further by remembering the context around the habit.
  </p>

  <h2>Track the number. Keep the story.</h2>
  <p>
    `20 minute walk` is useful data. `Skipped gym after a rough night, but walked 20 minutes after lunch` is useful
    memory. The second note explains the fallback, the constraint, and the fact that the routine survived in a smaller
    form.
  </p>

  <h2>Minimal still matters</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Fast capture</strong> — add a value or raw note in seconds.</li>
    <li><strong>Sane defaults</strong> — repeat patterns without re-entering every detail.</li>
    <li><strong>Readable views</strong> — categories, charts, and timeline make history easy to scan.</li>
    <li><strong>Forgiving workflow</strong> — missing a day never breaks the system.</li>
    <li><strong>Context when needed</strong> — add why, what changed, or how it felt without opening another app.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>A quieter definition of consistency</h2>
  <p>
    Consistency is not a perfect streak. Sometimes it is choosing the smallest version that still fits the day. Memoato
    is designed to help you see that difference instead of reducing every imperfect day to a failure.
  </p>

